"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-29-olympics-schedule-results-today-diving-swimming-gymnastics-21313308\", \"text\": \"The third day of theOlympic Gamesin Paris is underway with 18 gold medals up for grabs.  Tom Daley and Noah Williams got the day off to a superb startby securing silver in themen's synchronised 10m platform final. The British duo fell just short of gold withChina's Lian Junjie and Yang Hao turning in a series of flawless dives to claim gold.  Team GB's wait for a gold medal came to an end with the eventing team securing top spot. Laura Collett, Tom McEwan and Ros Canter, sealed victory in Monday's final showjumping stage.  Tom Pidcock was another to defend his crown, clinching gold after his incredible comeback culminated in a wild finale in the men's mountain bike race and he joinedthe growing list of Team GB medal winners at the Games.  Max Whitlock is seeking to become the first gymnast to win medals on the same apparatus at four successive Olympic Games with Team GB through to the men's gymnastics final.  And we will also get ourfirst look at Delicious Orie, the super-heavyweight looking to follow in the footsteps of his hero Anthony Joshua as he begins his quest for boxing gold.  This blog is now closed. For the latest updates, visitMetro's Sport page.  Here's a look at the gold medal events on Day 4 of the Paris 2024 Olympics\\u2026  Artistic gymnastics(women's team final),fencing(women's epee team),judo(women's -63kg, men's -81 kg),rugby sevens(women's),shooting(mixed team 10m air pistol, men's trap),surfing(men's and women's),swimming(women's 100m back, men's 800m free, men's 4x200m free relay),table tennis(mixed doubles),triathlon(men's individual).  So plenty more medal opportunities for Team GB. Until then, goodnight!  Team GB will be delighted with their efforts on day three of the Paris 2024 Olympics.  They added six medals to their tally, moving up to seventh in the medal table.  Team GB medals on Day 3:    A despondent Delicious Orie has reacted to his shock defeat at the Olympics.Find out what he said here.  Much was expected of Delicious Orie over in Paris but the Team GB boxer is out of the men's 92kg competition.  The 27-year-old lost to Armenia's Davit Chaloyan via a split decision and this one could proveverycontroversial\\u2026  It's all over for Delicious Orie at#Paris2024\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0098\\u00a9Armenia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Davit Chaloyan gets the win by split decision.#BBCOlympics#Olympicspic.twitter.com/NUau9Vkqh1  Mona McSharry not only clinched Ireland's first medal of the Olympics but also her nation's first swimming medal since 1996.  'I can not really ask for anything more than winning a medal at the Olympics,' she said.  'I am not even sure that was something that little me dreaming of going to the Olympics thought was possible.  'I am really just trying to keep pushing. That is what I have been training for all year, to be top three, and yeah dreams do come true.'  Yes! Well done Mona McSharry! Was at her semi-final last night, where she was brilliant, and now look at her!  A rare bit of bad news for Team GB on a largely successful day at the Games.  The Team GB women's team are out of the rugby sevens after losing 7-17 to USA, who progress to tomorrow's semi-finals.    Mona McSharry has won Ireland's first medal of the 2024 Olympic games in Paris with a bronze in the Women's 100m breaststroke final.  McSharry finished behind South Africa's Tatjana Smith and China's Tang Qianting. Team GB's Angharad Evans had to settle for fourth.  Swimming expert Karen Pickering said: 'Tatjana Smith brought that race home, she timed it to perfection.  'But Mona McSharry can not quite believe it, the Irish flags in the crowd are waving and the family and friends we saw earlier with the McSharry t-shirts will be absolutely delighted.'  That moment you realise you are an Olympic medallist.What a stunning effort by Mona McSharry to win bronze in the 100m breaststroke.Superb stuff from the Sligo star\\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a5\\u0089pic.twitter.com/V1NBg87CNX  Matt Richards produced a superb performance to clinch silver but should it have been even better for the 21-year-old?  The man himself and several BBC pundits suspect so\\u2026  Just 0.02 in it!!Matt Richards takes silver by a fingernail \\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a5\\u0088#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/Ymaef7Npmk  What a performance from Matt Richards. He's in contention throughout and finishes just 0.02 seconds behind Romania's David Popvic.  That is Team GB's sixth medal on what some are describing as 'Magic Monday' and their 10th overall of the Paris 2024 Games.  Over in the pool, Canada's 17-year-old sensation Summer McIntosh has absolutely stormed to gold in the women's 400m individual medley.  Britain's Freya Colbert almost bagged a medal - eventually finishing fourth - while fellow Team GB star Katie Shanahan was seventh.  \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00a8\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00a6\\u00e2\\u0098\\u0080\\u00ef\\u00b8\\u008f\\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a5\\u0087GOLD FOR MCINTOSH!!!\\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a5\\u0087\\u00e2\\u0098\\u0080\\u00ef\\u00b8\\u008f\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00a8\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00a6Summer McIntosh WINS the 400m IM and has her first Olympic gold to add to the Olympic silver in the 400m free.2 World Championship 400m IM golds, and she's now a#Paris2024champion.What a race. What an athlete.pic.twitter.com/Cdv1IWJlRS  The Chinese team looked almost shell-shocked after squandering their gold medal hopes.  You have got to feel for Su Weide, whofell twice in a terrible horizontal bars routine to allow Japan to pinch gold.  Team GB came close to another medal but can be proud with their efforts, according to ex-gymnastics star Beth Tweddle.  'Team GB can be very proud of themselves,' she told BBC One. 'It is 18 routines that we are asking for, which is tough.  'It was not down to one error, they were a couple of marks behind in the end.  'It was always going to be a tough challenge to get a medal and they have still got lots of individual and the women's final to come.'  Japan have won gold in the men's team gymnastics final in dramatic fashion, with China falling away late in the competition.  Su Weide twice fell on the high bar in his last event, seeing Team China fall from a position of dominance, with Japan's Hashimoto Daiki avoiding the same kind of mistake and winning gold for his country, although it was still incredibly close.  USA impressed and were the unlikely bronze medalists behind China, with Team GB finishing in fourth.  Max Whitlock, Joe Fraser, Jake Jarman, Harry Hepworth and Luke Whitehouse put in a strong showing, but narrowly missed out on medals.  Team GB confirmed on Monday that Charlie Carvell has withdrawn from Paris 2024 due to injury.  The sprinter posted two days ago on hisInstagram: 'I am devastated, I am being withdrawn from the Paris Olympics due to a minor hamstring issue.  'I will be taking a break from the sport and social media for a little while.'  Japan's Horigome Yuto has defended his men's street skateboarding Olympic title, winning gold ahead of USA's Jagger Eaton taking silver and Nyjah Huston bronze.  Yuto Horigome goes back-to-back! \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00af\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00b5\\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a5\\u0087 Gold in Tokyo\\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a5\\u0087 Gold in ParisDefending his street skateboarding title.#BBCOlympics#Olympics#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/C3ts7U1q01  It's two defeats from two for Team GB in women's hockey after a 4-0 loss to Australia.  Bottom of Pool B, qualification for the knockouts is not impossible, but already very difficult.  Asked how long he has dreamt of Olympic success, Adam Burgess told the BBC after silver in canoe slalom: 'Since I was like 10 years old! It's what I was thinking about in the start pool, I just wanted to do that kid proud, that dreamt of this moment. Go out there and give it my all and here we are.'  Adam Peaty posted a lengthy post following his silver medal on Sunday, which included a statement on his positive Covid test.  'I will now be focusing on a fast, full recovery to give my best in the team relays later in the week,' he wrote.  Rafael Nadal snapped at reporters after being asked about his retirement plans following a humbling defeat to Novak Djokovic at the Paris Olympics.  Stefanos Tsitsipas beats Dan Evans 6-1 6-2 in the men's singles, with the Brit back in action in the doubles alongside Andy Murray on Tuesday.  ArrowMORE:Olympics schedule and results: Andy Murray keeps medal dream alive as Team GB swimmers take gold  ArrowMORE:Pollution forces delay of men's Olympics triathlon in the River Seine  ArrowMORE:Team GB gold medallist felt 'a bit sad to be British' before Paris Olympics  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"